      "Callisto: one of Artemis's attendants, sworn to chastity. Zeus disguises himself as Artemis (or Diana) to get close to her and rapes her. Her pregnancy is revealed when the girls bathe — Diana expels her in anger. Hera (or Artemis/Diana in some versions) turns her into a bear; her son Arcas almost kills her hunting; Zeus places them both in the sky as Ursa Major and Ursa Minor (or Boötes). In Ovid it is Juno (not Diana) who punishes Callisto — an important distinction",
      "Niobe: boasts her 14 children surpass Leto's two (Apollo and Artemis) → Apollo kills all 7 sons, Artemis kills all 7 daughters. Niobe weeps herself into a rock — archetypal hubris myth. Artemis and Apollo act together as punishers of offenses against their mother",
      "Orion: famous hunter who tries to rape Artemis — she summons a scorpion from the earth to sting him to death (in one version). Another version: Artemis accidentally kills him while he is swimming (tricked by Apollo). Both versions end in his death and placement in the sky as the constellation Orion, with Scorpius nearby",
      "Arethusa: hunting nymph, follower of Artemis; river god Alpheus falls in love and pursues her; Artemis saves her by transforming her into a spring underground, flowing to Sicily (spring at Syracuse)",
      "Tiresias parallel: saw Athena bathing (in another myth) and was blinded — same motif as Actaeon with Artemis. Voyeurism of the divine punished",
      "Brauron (Brauronia): festival of Artemis 32 km southwest of Athens; the Arkteia — young girls (ages 5–10) had to 'play the bear' before they could marry. Girls wore saffron robes, made processions, sacrificed to Artemis. Important transition ritual for girls into womanhood. Women also made dedications to Artemis at Brauron after childbirth and for the health of their children",
      "Connection to Iphigenia: Agamemnon's daughter; Artemis becalmed the Greek fleet at Aulis; demanded Iphigenia as sacrifice; in some versions substituted a deer and took Iphigenia to Tauris as her priestess",
      "Artemis is also linked to death: in the Odyssey, Odysseus asks the spirit of his mother whether Artemis brought sudden death to her (women who died suddenly were said to be struck by Artemis's arrows — parallel to Apollo for men)"
