      "Homeric Hymn to Aphrodite (7th c. BCE): key poem for the course. Zeus grows tired of Aphrodite making gods sleep with mortals and turns the tables — makes Aphrodite fall in love with the mortal shepherd Anchises on Mount Ida. She disguises herself as a mortal princess; seduces him; later reveals she is a goddess; tells him their son will be Aeneas (future founder of Rome in Virgil's Aeneid). The poem explores: irony that Aphrodite is conquered by her own power; the danger to a mortal man of sleeping with a goddess (he could be left weakened/unmanned)",
      "Aphrodite in the Iliad: causes the Trojan War through the Judgment of Paris (bribes Paris with Helen). In Book 3, Paris is about to be killed by Menelaus — she rescues him in a cloud and transports him to his bedroom; tells Helen to go to him. Helen at first resists; Aphrodite threatens her; Helen gives in. Helen's psychology is complex — both victim and willing participant",
